res workers to actively win favor with managers in order to receive "schedule gifts": more or better hours. Wood concludes that the centrality of precarious scheduling to control means that for those at the bottom of the postindustrial labor market the future of work will increasingly be one of flexible despotism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFlexible work arrangementszGreat Britain. 0aFlexible work arrangementszUnited States. 0aHours of laborzGreat Britain. 0aHours of laborzUnited States. 0aIndustrial relationszGreat Britain. 0aIndustrial relationszUnited States. 0aPrecarious employmentzGreat Britain. 0aPrecarious employmentzUnited States. 4aHumanities & Human Rights. 4aLabor History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aAnticommunism, Philippines, US empire, decolonization, Cold War.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz97831107047230 cprintz978150174889940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501748905?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501748905423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501748905/original  a978-3-11-069046-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 En